attributes.descriptionHtml:
Nope, this listing isn't for a dog...it's for human volunteer help!

Read more about us at https://artbar-wv.org/faps

We are part of a network of rescues and shelters seeking volunteer drivers for dog transports in WV, KY, MD, PA, NJ, CT, MA & NY. General transfer points are listed in the drivers questionnaire so potential drivers can see if you live near our transport route.

Our transports start Saturday morning in northern WV. We overnight a few dogs in NJ and then finish up into New England on Sunday mornings.

We move dogs from rural shelters in WV & KY prescreened/approved organizations in the northeast. All dogs travel with appropriate vetting and paperwork. Crates are required but not provided, although we do occasionally get some donated to be shared among our driver network.

If you would like to help, please submit a driver application:


http://form.jotform.us/form/50214993744156

If the above didn't come through as a link, just copy and paste it into your browser to open the application. This listing exports from RescueGroups to dozens of websites, all of which have different rules about whether or not they allow clickable links in listings.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Poor Tiger! He has to be wondering if he will ever be adopted. Tiger has been with FHS for over three years now and we can't understand why. He is smart! He is sweet! He is loveable! As a kitten, Tiger nearly drowned as a tiny kitten in the spring downpours of 2015 when a neglectful neighbor left him and his siblings in a cage unprotected. But that didn't stop Tiger—he bounced back and embraced people and life with all four paws. He is independent and would be good with older and not too demanding children. As he gets older he is not as sociable with other cats and he doesn't like dogs, but funny thing is, he acts like a dog. So, whether you like playing football or watching football, Tiger is your buddy, just fill out an application at www.friscohumanesociety.com or call 972-489-8980 to meet him.

attributes.descriptionHtml: My name is Blaine. I am a very handsome guy that is quite shy. I tend to hide when I see people, so you have to come looking for me. Once you find me and start petting me, I will let you know how much I enjoy it by purring. I need a quiet home with a patient person that will give me time to adjust, gain confidence and come out of my shell. attributes.descriptionHtml:
My name is Alvin, If you are looking for a buddy to snuggle on the couch with, I am your guy! I also like to play with squeaky toys and soccer balls. I came from Arkansas back in the day, where I had a rough start and I sometimes am selective of my dog friends. After a proper introduction with new dogs though, I love to play with them. 
 
Not to brag, but I am really smart, too! I have completed obedience 1 class and know a lot of verbal commands and I'm eager to learn more!! I like to make my people happy and smile, I'll smile back! I am very food motivated, so if you want to teach me even more it won’t be hard! I Love my food puzzle and keeping my mind and body active. I'd be the best co-pilot in the car! I am also kennel trained and have learned how to walk with a gentle leader so I don’t pull so much. And yes, I'm house trained, what do you think I am an animal?!  I do not like cats and get very nervous around children so I would do best in a home without either. Looking for a mature home that has had some dog experience. I wouldn’t mind being the only dog so I can get lots of love and attention, but I would also be happy with another doggy friend as long as we are a good fit. I’m eagerly waiting for someone to please! 
 
Alvin's adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, altered and current on vaccinations and preventatives.  Our adoption process includes reference and background checks, a vet check and a home visit.

My name is Bingo. I have been waiting for more than 3 years for somebody to adopt me.  I am often told how adorable I am.  I am 4.5 years old, weigh 52 pounds and I am proud to be a bulldog/hound mix.  I was rescued from a high kill shelter and now I would like a home to call my own please.  

I have a lot of energy so I am looking for some humans that have a strong leader who will make sure I get enough exercise, structure and training.  I am a very loyal fur kid and once I trust you, I will love you and protect you forever! I do not like cats and I am a little picky about other dogs.  If you let me meet your other dog first, I will like them after I get to know them a bit.  Also, I am best around older, considerate children.  

 My adoption fee is $150 and it includes spay/neuter, rabies vaccine, DHPP, and microchip.  To have a meet and greet with me, please complete an application on our website: www.pawprinthearts.com

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Tina is one of our very special rescues, having been with us for basically all of her life after coming to us as a puppy in 2013. While we've had her for adoption since and even at some of our events, Tina just doesn't "show well" which has led to her being with us for so long. But that doesn't mean that she isn't a simply wonderful girl and well deserving of her own home.

Tina was brought to us as a puppy of only about 3 months of age. When her former owner asked if we could take her and her brother, Tuck, into our rescue, we had to ask him to bring them back in a couple of days so that we could prepared a kennel for them. Altho the man agreed, he simply left our rescue and then abandoned both pups into the yard of a lady, who witnessed his actions, and drove away. The following day, the woman brought both pups to us and told us what this man had done.

Tina has grown into a very loving and devoted dog to those she knows. She will bark defensively at strangers but after she gets to know someone, she is very affectionate towards them. You have to realize that Tina's "home" has been our rescue and she acts with us as she would if she'd been in a home for these past few years. But we're confident that if just the right person comes along, someone willing to be a little patient with her, then they'll be gaining a wonderful and devoted companion. 

Over the years Tina has been kept up to date on all of her yearly vaccinations, wormings and monthly preventatives, which has also led her to being heart worm negative. She's definitely a healthy girl who could even stand to loose a few pounds! Of course she'll need some training to become fully acclimated to living in a home but we'd expect that she'd pick up on those qualities rather quickly. If another dog is to be included in the home, a meet and greet would be required prior to the adoption. We don't know how she'll be with cats as she's never been around them.

If you can find it in your heart to give this very special girl the opportunity that she deserves, then please submit an application at socorescue.com

Tuck is one of our very special rescues, having been with us for basically all of his life after coming to us as a puppy in 2013. While we've had him for adoption since and even at some of our events, Tuck just doesn't "show well" which has led to him being with us for so long. But that doesn't mean that he isn't a simply wonderful fellow and well deserving of his own home.

Tuck was brought to us as a puppy of only about 3 months of age. When his former owner asked if we could take him and his sister, Tina, into our rescue, we had to ask him to bring them back in a couple of days so that we could prepared a kennel for them. Although the man agreed, he simply left our rescue and then abandoned both pups into the yard of a lady, who witnessed his actions, and drove away. The following day, the woman brought both pups to us and told us what this man had done.

Growing up in the rescue, Tuck has become accustomed to life at SoCo Rescue. While he is very friendly to those of us that he knows, he will  bark defensively at strangers.  But after he gets to know someone, he is very friendly towards them. We're confident that if just the right person comes along, someone willing to be a little patient with him, then they'll be gaining a wonderful and devoted companion. Tuck does love a good game of fetch and his doggie treats, both of which are good ways to make friends with this big, lovable fellow.

Over the years Tuck has been kept up to date on all of his yearly vaccinations, wormings and monthly preventatives, which has also led him to being heart worm negative. He's definitely a healthy boy who could even stand to loose a few pounds! Of course he'll need some training to become fully acclimated to living in a home but we'd expect that he'd pick up on those qualities rather quickly.

 

If another dog is to be included in the home, a meet and greet would be required prior to the adoption. We don't know how he'll be with cats as he's never been around them.

I adore people and get along will with other felines (as long as I am in charge) but I'm an independent kitty, so I'm not the clingy type. Our website is updated daily

Hope is spayed, UTD on vaccines and tested negative for FIV/FeLV. Approx. DOB is January 2014.

Hope and her companions were taken into foster by NAR in September 2015 when their owner could no longer care for them.  Hope has been the most outgoing of the group.  She was a little hissy at first, but was not trying to hide in her new room like the others.  Hope wandered around, investigating everything.  After a few days, she felt at home and she's been very friendly since then, always looking for attention. 

It took some time, but now she gets along with all the other cats and 2 large dogs she lives with.  She loves people and will sit nearby and sleep with you whenever she can.

If interested in adopting Hope, please fill out an application online at http://nar.rescuegroups.org.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Oscar was rescued with his little Buddy, Felix.  They came from a North GA shelter as part of a hoarding case.  Oscar is extremely timid and takes a while to warm up to you, and even then, he only lets you pet under his chin, sometimes you can scratch behind his ears, but he runs away if you raise your hand to pet his head or back.  We have been unable to catch him except to throw a treat in a crate.  He will jump on your legs for a treat and follow you around all day.  He likes the company of all dogs and is very playful, especially with his friend, Felix.  For this reason, they should be adopted together.  Felix gives him courage to approach you upon first meeting. Oscar is going to take some work, and needs a patient and understanding rescue-minded, dog-experienced adopter.  Even though his foster mom can't pick him up yet to hug him and snuggle with him, he has wormed his way into her heart, and she looks forward to giving him the little bit of affection he allows. When he finally comes out of his shell, someone is going to have a wonderful little dog.

Alcovy dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on all vaccines, up to date on heart-worm preventative and flea preventative and micro-chipped. If interested in adoption, please complete an online application on Alcovy Pet Rescue's website at www.alcovypet.com. You must have a vet reference to adopt. We verify the care of past/current pets. Applications without a vet reference will not be approved for adoption. Our goal is to have the very best home for all our dogs and cats and therefore we reserve the right to approve or deny an application based on what we determine is in the pet's best interest.

attributes.breedString: Yorkshire Terrier Yorkie / Chihuahua / Mixed (medium coat)
attributes.descriptionHtml:
Felix was rescued with his Buddy, Oscar. They came from a North GA shelter as part of a hoarding case.  Felix is a timid little guy and takes a while to warm up to you, and even then, he only lets you pet him for a brief moments.  He's hard to catch unless you throw a treat in a crate. It is possible to catch him and pick him up, but he freezes and pees a little bit. He allows his foster mom to hold him and kiss him, but not for long - he starts squirming to get away. He will jump on your legs for a treat and follow you around all day. He is paper-trained. He likes the company of most small dogs and is very playful, especially with his friend, Oscar.  For this reason, they should be adopted together. He can be bossy and barky to bigger dogs. Felix is going to take some work, and needs a patient and understanding rescue-minded, dog-experienced adopter. The small bits of affection he allows is worth the wait. When he finally comes completely out of his shell, someone is going to have a wonderful little dog.

Alcovy dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on all vaccines, up to date on heart-worm preventative and flea preventative and micro-chipped. attributes.descriptionHtml:
SPECIAL! We are overrun with MANY wonderful male Great Pyrenees! The shelters are packed with dogs that people are returning since going on vacation post-COVID! For any new applications received from May 15 to August 15, adoption fee is ONLY $250 (includes neuter, distemper /parvo shot, rabies shot, heartworm testing, heartworm and flea prevention and USDA health certificate to travel.) These wonderful dogs desperately need YOU to give them a great home!! (Transportation fee of $225 is paid separately to independent transporter).

Buddy truly lives up to his name. Born around March 2014, Buddy is a friendly, woolly presence wherever you are: calm and well-mannered in the house, in the car, and on walks; he makes friends everywhere he goes.

A bump on the ground most of the time, he launches himself so wholeheartedly into action when the doorbell rings that it’s funny to see! Once he’s had a chance to sniff your visitors, he’s generally okay and may even hug them. He barks when he sees or hears anything unusual in the garden but will stop as soon as he knows you’ve checked it out and are fine with it.

He loves to chase bunnies and will bounce after them across the lawn like a big furry beach ball but has been good with the horse, goat, sheep, and chickens. The cat’s not keen on him but will walk by or even jump over him, and he mostly ignores her.

A great pal, and easy-going, as long as he can be with you, but though he doesn’t seem to mind waiting for you in the car, he gets very anxious if he thinks he’s been left alone in the house and will either start howling or try to get out to start looking for you. An adopter would have to be willing to take him along, or have somebody stay with him, all the time. Buddy’s foster Mom says, “He gets along well with my female and smaller male dogs, but he isn’t crazy about my larger Pyr, so maybe best with female or smaller dogs than him.” He can be adopted as an one-and-only, too. He likes kids but would be best in a home with just adults.

ADOPT HERE: Complete an Adoption Application for your Pyr-fect new family companion at https://gprs.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=6206.

All dogs and puppies require VISIBLE fencing

Adoption fee: $250 (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225).

GPRS has proudly placed thousands of Great Pyrenees and GP mixes in the PNW for over a decade. Our volunteers have over 100 years combined experience fostering, screening, and placing this majestic breed into loving, forever homes. When adopting from us, you can rest assured that we provide life-long support and advice when it comes to your new family member. As always, our purpose is to find the best match for every unique dog that comes through our doors. Taking the time to find the right fit comes first and foremost at the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society. If you are interested in adopting, please take the time, and apply. You will see firsthand how much care, attention and love goes into the process, when you are guided a personal screener. This is why we have people come back again and again for their next family member! See all our dogs, fill out an application and discover why we are the BEST at placing the right dog in the right home! https://gprs.rescuegroups.org/.

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer.

FOSTER HERE: Apply to foster at dog at https://gprs.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=6281 .

VOLUNTEER HERE: Let us know your interests in helping our Pyr friends at https://gprs.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=6272.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Hi, my name is Chucha and I hit the jackpot when nowzad took me in.

I came into the nowzad shelter in September 2014, I was originally part of a TNVR effort in the local area of the shelter but once I had been fixed and vaccinated I decided I did not want to leave the shelter where I had been given love and food and warmth.

I settled into the routine at the shelter quickly and I was good with the other dogs but now I am yearning for a family to call my own.  I am happy to be in a single dog or multi dog household.

I have no real training to speak of but I learn very quickly.  I am not overly playful but I do love being cuddled by the humans around me.  I have not been tested with cats.

I am spayed, vaccinated and chipped and in good health with no known issues.

‘This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting, then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home’.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Hi, my name is Spartus and I am looking for a new family.

I was born on 25 Dec 2013 and came into the nowzad shelter when an Afghan lady came across me and my siblings in the street and saw that our mom had died. We were only a few days old and there was no chance of surviving on the streets without our mom but thankfully the nowzad shelter took us in.

As we were so young when we came in we had to be hand reared by the shelter staff. Some of my siblings have found new homes in the USA and the UK and I am now looking for that special family of my own.

I am a large breed dog and have high energy levels so will need an active family. I love being around people but will need some work on my manners as I get very excited at times.

I can walk on a leash, I am not housetrained as I have lived all my life in the shelter but I learn quickly and am very intelligent.

I am neutered and have no known health issues.

‘This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting, then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home’.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
My name is Zoey and I need a family. I came into the Nowzad shelter with my siblings in 2014, I was only about 8 weeks old. I had been found on the streets of Kabul and my mom was nowhere to be seen. I am a typical teenage dog who needs a lot of love and attention and would be best suited to an active family. I am fine with other dogs, I have not been tested with cats. I do have fairly long hair so I will need a family who are happy to keep me groomed. I need some training, I have never lived indoors so I am not housetrained but I am clever and quick to learn. I can walk on a leash but I will need practice with this as I have never been walked outside of the shelter. I am spayed, microchipped and have no known health issues.

‘This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting, then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home’.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
I am Fluffy and I found myself at the nowzad shelter when I was a tiny kitten barely old enough to be away from my mom.  I had been found in the street by and Afghan national who had been worried about leaving me in the street alone.

I was quickly given a clean bill of health by the nowzad vets and received my chip, vaccinations and neuter.  I get on really well with other cats but most of all I adore sitting on peoples laps.  I give out lots of kisses and demand constant love and cuddles.

I am on good health with no known health issues.

attributes.breedString: Anatolian Shepherd / Labrador Retriever / Mixed (medium coat)
attributes.descriptionHtml:
I am Alfie, I came to the attention of nowzad when some kind people spotted me roaming round an Afghan Government compound.  My nose was raw and bleeding and so swollen my nostrils were the size of pinholes. 

The nowzad team quickly came to the compound to try and catch me but I was scared and kept running off.  The day they came was a cold and wet day and I eventually hid underneath a shipping container so there was no way they could get me.  The nowzad team left and spoke to some policemen in the area to let them know I was sick and needed help and the very next day the policemen managed to catch me and take me to the clinic.  The Nowzad team helped heal me and I am a healthy dog now.  

Ideally I need an active family, I do great with other dogs but will chase cats.  I also like the sound of my own voice so I will need to be worked with to teach me when it is appropriate to bark and when it isn't!

I have no known health issues, I am neutered, chipped and vaccinated.

‘This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting, then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home’.

‘This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting, then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home’.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
I am Arpana, I was born into a litter of 6 other pups.  We had a reasonably good life living outside of a foreign compound in Kabul until one day a huge explosion changed everything for us.

We were about 5 weeks old, our mom and the guards at the compound had done a great job of raising us then one day a truck bomb exploded outside the compound and killed our mom.  We were saved because our mom had kept us hidden.  The guards at the compound continued to take care of us and a few days later they reported to the foreigners that our mom had been killed in the attack and although they were doing their best to help us they needed help so we were brought to the nowzad shelter.

At first we were completely terrified, in a few short days we had been involved in a huge bomb blast, lost our mom and now we were in a totally new place with people we had never seen before.  It did not take us long to realise the people at the nowzad clinic were going to help us and we soon settled into several good meals a day and plenty of play time.

I am still a little skittish of people I am not familiar with but with time I will become a faithful and loyal pet.  I am good with other dogs, I have not been formally introduced to cats but it is felt that with my calm nature I would not be a problem with cats if introduced slowly.

I am chipped, vaccinated and fixed with no known health issues

‘This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting, then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home’.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Hi, my name is Fritzi.  I have been here at the shelter for five years now.  I had never been socialize well with people before arriving and consequently would avoid all contact with staff and visitors for most of that time.  Thanks to a wonderful volunteer, I am doing sooo much better.  He spends time with me and most importantly allows me to interact at my own speed.  I don't cringe when someone comes near.  I feel more relaxed and am able to enjoy my toys. I especially love that laser light.  Early on, I developed stomatitis a condition that made my gums and mouth sore.  I had to have dental cleanings and be put on medicine to help me feel better.  Through the years many of my teeth had to be removed  and now I no longer have any.  This has been a good thing because I am really able to enjoy my wet food now.  I have been told I have a beautiful gray with white coat and the prettiest green eyes. Please  think of me when wanting to adopt.  I may not be a lap cat right away but will do my best to fit in to your home.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
In her own words:  I was saying to myself just this morning "Venus, you know what you need? You need a person all your own."  So I sat down to write this post for the nice people at HOPE, because  that's the kind of thing they do - find nice people for extremely intelligent and lovable furbabies.  I shudder to type this, but I'm LAPLESS! That's right, I have no human lap to call my own. Could you be persuaded to volunteer yours?  I can't wait to see my forever home!"

Venus is an active and incredibly smart girl who likes nothing more than to stretch her legs at the beach or at the park.  She'd suit an active person who wants an outgoing and friendly companion - if you can lob a tennis ball, Venus will be your friend for life!  She would like to be the only pet in her new home.

If you are interested in Venus and would like to fill out a Dog Adoption Application, please go to: http://www.homelesspets.net/adoption-forms/dog-adoption.php . Submitting an application does not obligate you to adopt from us but it initiates contact with us and gets the process started. If you have questions prior to filling out the application, email us at HOPEDogCommittee@groups.io and a volunteer will get back to you.
attributes.name: Venus

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Name: Ellen kna. Rainey
Date of Birth: Approx. 10/26/14
Gender: Female
Breed: Pitty
Weight: 45
Dog friendly: Yes
Cat friendly: Yes
Kid friendly: Yes
House trained: Yes  
Crate trained: Yes
Energy level: Moderate 
History: Pulled from a high kill shelter
Adoption Fee: $500

From the Foster:    Rainy would do best with an owner that could make her #1. She is good with kids insofar as she is a very loving dog at heart and has lived with children, but she is also very shy initially and I think it would be best if she could be with someone that gave her most of the attention, so someone with older kids or no kids would likely be easiest. She is shy - again, initially, after she is comfortable she is very outgoing and friendly - but has NEVER shown aggression. Her base temperament is all love. She loves to run around and play but her favorite thing to do is snuggle up and relax on the couch or the bed with her human friends. I’m sure there is someone out there that would love a very well-behaved, teachable, house-trained, very loving dog like Rainy to snuggle up with every day. Please let me know if anyone has interest and wants to meet her or ask me any questions.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Chance is an older gentleman. He is a German Shepherd mix. Chance is a very sweet and loving boy. He is very affectionate. Strangers do make him nervous, he needs some time to warm up to you so that he knows he can trust you. He is crate trained, leash trained and house broken. Chance would do best in a quiet home with no cats and possibly a calm quiet female dog. Toddlers make him nervous so he would do better with older children. He loves following his foster parents around his big fenced in yard and will play with you with a toy. He also loves going on walks and car rides . Chance would love a family that is retired or semi retired and able to spend time with him. If you think Chance is the perfect fit for you or your family please apply online at www.onedogatatime.us

attributes.descriptionHtml: Hey there, my name is Jersey. I've heard some silly talk that all black cats look alike. Come on now, we come in all different shapes and sizes with distinguishing features and certainly different personalities. Me personally I am sweet, affectionate, playful and inquisitive with a slender build and soft amber colored eyes. I am game for anything from playing and exploring to snuggling and napping. I'm not a high maintenance diva. Give me a wadded up piece of paper to chase, a simple box, a warm sunny spot or warm lap and all is good. I'm a light traveler, no baggage here.

Annie was found on someone's porch, pregnant and starving. She stayed for a couple of weeks, until she got into the neighbor's dog food, when the neighbor threatened to take her life. A good samaritan intervened and Annie became a member of the Rescue Dogs Rock NYC family. Born in late 2013, our Mastiff/ Boxer mix would do best in an adult-only home, with no other pets, in a quiet suburb. She needs an adopter experienced with large breed dogs. Annie is 85 pounds and is a very strong girl. She's very affectionate, housetrained, and loves to be with her people!!   To adopt Annie, please put your application in here:  http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc                                                         

RDR's adoption fees include the cost of spay/neuter/microchip at an RDR-approved facility, whether completed before adoption or if deferred because the pet is too young or has a medical issue.  All pets are also current on age-appropriate vaccines at the time of adoption

Given technical constraints on this database, this pet's location may not be as listed here. We can, however, provide transport support for pets in foster at a considerable distance from the adopter.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
There is only one queen in the Adopt-A-Dog castle and that is Ella! 

Ella is an absolute sweetheart and we could not imagine a sweeter companion to be by your side. She is equal parts sugar and spice and is more than ready to join you on a walk around the neighborhood or for fetch in the yard. As one of our office dogs, Ella has proven time and time again that both her filing skills and ability to consume the office snacks are unparalleled. She brings joy to everyone with her endless butt wiggles and enthusiasm.

Most who have met Ella are surprised to hear that she is a senior because of how bouncy she is. She came to us from Yonkers Animal Shelter, as an owner surrender. Ella had been the companion of an older person her whole life and when they were no longer able to care for her, her family had no place for her. At the city shelter, Ella was adored by the volunteers who saw just how kind and sweet she was. She is also a breast cancer survivor which makes her even more deserving of a home of her own. One can imagine how much love and devotion Ella had for her person and she is truly a "lovebug"; she shares her love and affection with every new person she meets and is just waiting for a family to call hers.

Not only is Ella queen of the castle, she rules benevolently and is more than happy to give kisses to any willing subject. She is a fabulous walker and can strut around the neighborhood with the best of them. Adding up all of her qualities, you would be hard-pressed to find a better companion. Won't you give this golden girl a home for her golden years?

 If you are interested in adopting Ella or any of our other adoptable dogs, please fill out the following online application here:  

https://forms.gle/pnkaGTG8Cy4dgQRJ8
attributes.name: Ella

attributes.descriptionHtml: Ellie is a wonderful, beautiful and very smart dog.  She gets along with other dogs very well, but can be a handful around smaller dogs.  She does not know here own size, but dogs her size are just fine.  She does not have a bad bone in her body.  She loves chewing on her kong, earning her treats.  She is leash trained and knows several hand signals.  We are still working with her on checking in regularly.  She has not been around kids, but cannot imagine that will be an issue with her temperament.  Ellie is deaf and has received professional training from On the Ball K9 Training in Denton, TX.  She will stay on your side but can get distracted.  She will sit and stay when told and is pretty content on her "place" as long as she has some entertainment.  She is crate trained and sleeps in a crate.  Her favorite activity is going on long walks, but even more, she will play fetch with you until she absolutely wears herself out.  And then, once you think she has had enough, she is ready for some more.  She loves fetching tennis balls and ropes throws...and will bring them back to you almost all of the time, unless she gets distracted.  She will then sit when you tell her and release the toy for another round.  Ellie was born mid-2015 and weighs approx 90 pounds.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Gizmo is 8 and 24 lbs of total cuteness. He's best for a more quiet home without kids where he can feel confident, and give you and get all the loves. An older person looking for a pal can work, too!

Gizmo wants to be the only pet, doesn't appear to like other animals much, maybe in due time. We know people are that way,  too, so why not a doggie?

Gizmo is a loving boy with people he trusts, but it takes him a little time to befriend new people but then his heart is yours. He is so loyal and extremely loving. He loves snuggle time. He is always so happy to see you walk in the door. He talks a lot with his funny and cute ways, telling you when he wants to eat or such, super comical and darling. He also is a neat and tidy boy. 

One of his fave things to do it go on car rides! 

Gizmo will thrive in a home with a yard. He loves his walks and we have tips on how to keep him focused so he isn't barking at other dogs. If your neighborhood is quiet, it is perfect for him! He thrives in the outdoors on long walks, esp on the beach, in the woods or wherever else great sniffing is offered!

Gizmo is a barker and we can provide tips but it is why we are seeking a more quiet neighborhood. He currently lives in a busy place and he may do really well right off the bat in a place with room.  He also is fiercely protective of his owner. We have tips and can help with introduction techniques so he learns who in the family is cool as a cat. 

He is now updated on all shots, neutered and chipped! His adopt fee is $295.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
My name is Nala, and I've been at PRBJ for roughly 4 years. I'm a good dog, and I love everyone that works here, but when I love someone I get very protective of them, but isn't that my job???
   I really need a home with a single person, someone that doesn't have any company over, and most importantly will be patient with me and see that I really only want to love my person and protect them.
   I was adopted for about 6 months and my owners loved me but when they would have people over, I became nervous and that became an issue for them. I bond easily with one person. I wish someone would give me a chance to show them what a good girl I am...
                    Love, Nala

Nala does best with an alpha/dominant breed owner. She needs a single owner whom she can bond with and feel confy around. A low traffic, quiet home, with fenced backyard is needed for her. At 6 yrs old, Nala is passed the energetic puppy/young adult stages and is content to play in the yard and then cuddle with her person inside. She would be perfect for a single person who works from at home where she can offer companinship, loyalty, and protection.
  Are you the person for Nala? Please submitt an application~

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Hi there, my name is Bossman - my foster mom says that's because I am the boss!  I am a 10 year old orange kitty cat.  I was recently saved from a local shelter but before finding my way there I was wandering the streets for a bit.  Life on the streets can be rough for a guy like me, but luckily I have lots of people looking out for me now.  I did have some matting due to being on the streets, so I needed a haircut.  My foster mom says I am still cute as a button, and my fur should grow back in soon.  I currently weigh in around 7 pounds but am hoping to pack some pounds on now that I am in a home.  I am snuggler and love my blanket.  I have excellent litter box habits and love my wet food.  At some point I must have had a family because I am missing my front claws.  Oh well, there loss is your gain because now I am in search of the purrfect family to love.  


All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, spayed/neutered, dewormed, heartworm tested and treated if necessary. Vet references are required and prior to adoption a home inspection will be conducted. Adoption fee applies.
If interested go to www.pmarinc.org for an application.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Fred is about 5 1/2 years old.  He's not a very big dog - weighs 42 lbs and comes up to my knees (I'm 5'4"). He is solid muscle!  He's a spoiled child - has to have all the dog toys so when we're looking for them, they can usually be found in his crate! He loves to run and play and be outside when the weather permits. He likes his belly rubbed and especially LOVES his back scratched! He is a loving boy and often will come sit with us with his head in our laps.  He is very loyal to his humans but prefers to be the only dog in the home. He is fully vetted - vaccinated, neutered, Rabies, microchipped, and is current on heartworm preventative.  His adoption fee is $150.

If you are interested in finding out more about Fred, you can email us at:  newbeginnings_animalrescue@yahoo.com.  If you would like to apply to adopt Fred, please click on this link to our online application:  https://form.jotform.com/NBAR/PetAdoptionApplication

Thank you for considering adopting a rescued pet!

I AM IN FOSTER CARE! PLEASE FILL OUT OUR ADOPTION APPLICATION, ONCE APPROVED, GIVE US A CALL AND WE CAN SET UP AN APPOINTMENT FOR YOU TO MEET ME!

I am 55lbs, 10 years young and seeking my forever home!

Adoption Donation: $100

I am great in the car and 100% housebroken.  I am a quiet, well behaved girl who is extremely loyal to my family.  I just want a quiet home with adults.

All dogs are microchippped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested (if age appropriate) and up to date on preventatives at the time of adoption.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of your appointment.

The shelter is currently open by appointment only with an approved application. Please note, all applications are considered general and stay on file for 6 months. Specific animals are NOT put on hold for adoption. When you visit, the adoption counselors will be able to make suggestions based on the type of pet you are looking for and help you find the best fit for your family.

Animal House Shelter cannot guarantee the breeds of the adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as the breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also cannot guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

We look forward to seeing you soon!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
In a Foster home !
A PRE-APPROVED application is required to meet Lucy. BY APPOINTMENT ONLY

Background: Stray

Personality: Firecracker, loves water and car rides. Loves to work on obedience training and enjoys having a job to do

Cats: No

Dogs: No

Kids: No..adults only (not even visiting kids)

Energy Level: High

Housebroken: Yes

Crate Trained: Yes

Prey for Wildlife(if high, no invisible fence) High

Fence required: Yes

Best home for this pet: Lucy is a high energy young adult who will need time and patience to adapt to change. She will require a calm, low traffic stable home. Once Lucy bonds, she settles in and loves to spend one on one time with her people.

Lucy Loo requires multiple meets by appt only.

We do our best to get to know each and every dog at our camp. Their personalities emerge after being with us for a bit and sometimes change. The personality and other information included in the above description is based on what we know currently in the shelter environment. All dogs are up to date on vaccines (Distemper, Rabies, Bordetella), microchipped, spayed/neutered and receive worming, flea & tick medication before they are adopted out. Please note there are some exceptions depending on the condition of the dog. If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application at https://www.camppapillon.org/dog-application.

Once your dog is in your home, they will adjust and relax and could become more playful or show more personality traits as they begin to open up. Once adopted, please allow your dog time to decompress and relax in a stable home environment.

Poor Marshall was surrendered to the Newark shelter when his owner could no longer care for him! He is 8 years old and requires a strong handler to help him become confident again.  Marshall is loving and sweet but will do best in a quiet home without a lot of visitors. He does get along with both dogs and cats - he is even okay with children but might do best in an adults-only home where there will be fewer comings and goings.

If you have the right kind of environment for Marshall, please consider giving him a one-way ticket out of the EHR kennel. You may fill out an adoption or foster application at www.ehrdogs.org, mentioning his name!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Would you get a look at those ears?

Lando has a personality as unique as his fantastic coat; he is arguably one of the coolest-looking dogs around. His ears alone are more than ready to listen to your next story while you're cruising around town. Goofy, energetic and a huge fan of toys, Lando is pretty easy to please. He is undoubtedly one of our favorite dogs to try new things and skills with as his earnestness and (sometimes) clumsiness means you will be entertained for hours.

Found as a stray in Yonkers, Lando arrived at the local shelter there. He eventually made his way to our shelter so that we could start giving him the training and extra care he needed to start his journey to finding a family of his own. Our volunteers and staff have made sure that Lando is always on the go, and weekly car rides to grab a McDonald's burger coupled with tug or agility in the yard is part of his daily routine. Now he just needs to find a drive-thru buddy of his own!

Lando is part of our Diamonds in the Ruff program, which means that his future family would be getting a fantastic dog that already has the training and skills he needs to transition successfully into a home. Ask our Adoptions Team what being a Diamond in the Ruff dog means and how to adopt one!


Contact the Adoptions team at (914) 273-1674 or adoptions@adoptadog,org for more information!

The first step to adopting one of our dogs is to fill out our online adoptions questionnaire located here: https://forms.gle/5heEH8S6c7zXBneD7

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Susie is a 5-year-old 25 pound lover! Susie was in a home for 4 years but recently came back to Eleventh Hour. Her owner's home situation changed and became too much for Susie to handle. She will need a lower traffic adult household as she can be protective of her owners and house. For Susie, the best situation would be a single adult who is willing and able to put Susie away when there is company over. Susie likes other dogs & cats, but she can be protective of her food, so really should be the only pet. Susie would do best in a home with someone who has dog experience, preferably with Boston Terriers and their specific behaviors. 

If you'd like to meet this sweet, funny gal please fill out an adoption application at www.ehrdogs.org & be sure to ask for her by name, SUSIE RM!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
My name is Rosco. I was rescued from the Bandera County Pound several years ago. The inmates took care of me at the old facility. They played with me and taught me to be a good boy. When they got full, they called AD4Y Rescue and asked them to save me and here I am.

You see I don't like change too much. I became very withdrawn when I left my friends at the jail. I had alot more room to run and play and frankly I did everything I could to stay away from the girls. I trusted Ms. Pat, but no one else was going to touch this bad boy. But they wouldn't give up.

Over the last 30 days they have been telling me they are going to get me adopted one way or the other. They told me I have to start being a good boy with strangers and letting new people meet me. I wasn't going to do it, but Ms. Pat made me play with Ms. Kim. Did you know she keeps yummy stuff in her pocket? I tried to resist, but did I mention it was yummy?

The next thing you know Ms. Kim was taking me on walks and introducing me to new things. You know what? Change really isn't all that bad. I have to admit I love the attention. I am still a little skittish of new people but I am learning to trust people. I even went to the beauty shop and had them cut my hair. It's normally a lot longer.

I love to go on walks, it is truly my favorite thing or is it treats..it’s a toss up. I even walk off leash at the ranch!  When I warm up to you I am just a big love bug. I give Ms. Kim kisses all the time. I like to chase a ball but I am getting older so I usually just chew on it when I catch it.  I have lived in a kennel now for awhile so I would need to be house trained again, but I am sure I can catch on fast, because I am super smart. I am doing great around other dogs too. I know that I can finally trust. I need to lose a little weight. I am slowing down but a nice orthopedic bed by you would be awesome.  So iff you have lots of time and patience to help me adjust I will be your best friend for life! 

If you would like to apply for me please go to www.adoggie4you.org and fill out a Companion Pet Application. If you want to help sponsor me, you can donate here. Your donations make sure other dogs like me have a chance at a new life, even if we are slow to adapt.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Sweet, Empathetic Brody Needs a Home to Call His Own!

Besides being super adorable and cuddly (and having the softest and warmest floppy ears), Brody is also uber sweet and sensitive.

This young boy’s story has not always been happy. He was found as a stray, abandoned by his adoptive family 90 miles from home. Thankfully he has retained his optimism, and continues to hope and trust that one day he will find his very own humans again to love him, be kind to him and make him the center of their world.

Brody – or Bro Bro as he prefers to be endearingly  addressed - is THE best hiking companion. He is energetic and thoroughly enjoys daily walks around the neighborhood. But he especially LOVES hiking adventures in the woods. Nothing makes him happier than car rides.

Bro Bro is also a big homebody and enjoys chillin’ in front of a good Netflix too. He loves piano music – his favorite spots in his foster family’s home are under the baby grand when it’s being played and on the couch snuggling on a quiet rainy day.

We believe that Bro Bro’s not-so-happy first part of his life has given him the special gift of empathy. He is ultra sensitive and attuned to the emotions of his humans. 

When he senses that people are sad, he has been known to promptly walk over and place his warm comforting head firmly on their lap as his way of saying, “Please feel better. Bro Bro is here for you forever and is your friend. I will snuggle with you now if you like.” 

He has a ridiculously adorable spazzy side too. And he most often exhibits that when his humans come home. That’s when he does The Dance - a combination of extreme butt wiggles and whirling dervish spinning while holding his favorite toy in his mouth.

Bro Bro will thrive in a home where he can shine as the only pet, and will be happiest with calm, kind and gentle adults who are experienced adopters and can continue to train him using the gentlest ways - we strongly recommend Jan Fennell’s Amichien Bonding method, rather than Cesar Milan’s physical domination approach. 

When Bro Bro knows in his heart that he is forever loved and is safe and will never be scolded, he will blossom and make you so proud by being your best and most loyal furry forever friend! ❤️

...If you live with an hour of Washington, D.C. and have a fenced yard, please apply to adopt this sweet soul! His adoption fee is $125, he is neutered, is current on rabies, dhpp, bordatella and has been on monthly preventatives for fleas/ticks and heartworms. He’s been getting the best nutrition possible too I might add. Best with no children in the home, adults ideal. This 7 year old boy needs you and you will be rewarded with his love in return! Please share this post also if you would!

Can you be his family?! Committed fosters or foster to adopt, please contact us also! Transport is available in VA or D.C area to an approved home.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Hi. My name is Giner. I came to the Olive Branch a a feral cat that had to be removed from my home. It has taken a lot of time, patience, and love, but I have finally become the sweet kitty I was destined to be. I love attention. especially scratches behind the ears and snuggling on your lap. I get along well with other cats, but I've never met a dog. I am spayed, feline leukemia negative, and all of my vaccinations are current. If you wouldd like to make me a part of your family, fill out the adoption application on this site.

My name is Mounty.  I was hit by a car and suffered major injuries to my legs and back.  The Nowzad team came to my rescue and helped me recover.  I still have problems walking and standing, but can get myself around.  With more therapy, I know I will be able to walk without bumping into things.  I am friendly towards humans and other dogs.  I have also been neutered, microchipped, and vaccinated.  Please adopt me.  My disabilities does not affect my love in any way.

‘This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting, then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home’.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Quick Facts:
Breed(s): Domestic Shorthair
Gender: Neutered Male
Age: 6 years
I’m good with: 
Dogs? Unknown    
Cats? Yes     
Kids? Older / Considerate Kids Only

History:
Croix was abandoned on the Hermitage's property in January of 2016. 

Personality:
Croix is a golden hearted happy boy who loves his pets. Understandably because of his not so great past experience with humans, it took Croix quite a bit to come out of his shell. The once shy baby who was unsure of humans is long gone and has become the official door greeter happy to escort any and all around his home. Croix LOVES treats and his yummy wet food and will do circles and happily chirp at you until he gets some! After all this amazing progress Croix just needs a family of his very own to love and spoil him like the good kitty he's truly turned out to be.  

Medical:
Croix is an adorable FIV+ kitty, our staff is happy to answer any questions you have about adopting an FIV+ cat!

attributes.descriptionHtml: 6 yrs old , super sweet, love baskets, bags, catnip and laser chasing. Wants quiet house as a solo cat or with non aggressive older cat. I’m Yaran.  I was born in an Afghan family home.  They could not keep all of us and our mom, so decided to keep our mom and send all of us to Nowzad.  My siblings have been all adopted, and I’m the only one still left.  I’m a friendly cat and love to cuddle.  I am also vaccinated and neutered.

 

This companion animal is currently in the Nowzad shelter in Kabul, Afghanistan. If you are interested in adopting then the Nowzad charity will supply you with video and photographs and should the adoption go ahead will fundraise and arrange the transport for this companion animal to come to your home.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Hi … my name is Mango Grace! Read my bio to find out everything you need to know about me.  

If you think I might be the perfect pup for you, go to www.allamericanmuttrescue.org/forms and complete the adoption application online.
If you can't adopt and meet her special needs, you can still help her by sponsoring her extended care with tax-deductible donations designated for Mango Grace's care.  

“Dogs do speak, but only to those who know how to listen.”– Orhan Pamuk (author, My Name Is Red)  Does Mango Grace speak to you?   She is a special gem in need of a special hero.

Mango was a stray who ‘picked’ a family that she found. All the people in the family loved her, but Mango’s high energy and exuberance proved to be too much for their older dogs.  Her play style with other dogs is a little rough-tumble and in-your-face, and not all other dogs are OK with that.  She does not always meet new people well, but once she trusts you, she is a velcro dog with her people. She loves her current foster mom, but for the first 3 days, she growled at her too. She still needs more socialization before she can be a 'go everywhere' dog. 

Mango will enjoy a new family with people who have time to spend with her, who are willing to take her to training, who are willing to make sure she gets plenty of exercise … who are willing to love her and work with her to become the best dog she can be. Could that be you?

Approximate age/birthdate:  born ~ April 2015

Weight/size: 45-50 lbs

Housebroken:  YES (if you do your part letting her out regularly)

Crate trained:  YES

Personality:  busy, wary of new people at first, playful

Energy level:  very energetic, rough and tumble play style
 
Fenced yard required?:   YES ... a physical fence (no underground/electric fences)  No Exceptions.  Mango would be a danger to neighborhood cats and possibly small dogs. She has a high prey drive.

Does he/she jump fences?  NO (but she could if she wanted to)

Leash walk:  YES … high energy so will still pull

Obedience training:  Knows ‘sit’

Riding in vehicles:  RIDES OK … gets a little stressed at first         

Spayed/neutered:   YES

Up-to-date on routine vaccinations:   YES

Microchipped:  NO but a chip will be provided

Social with other dogs:  YES but she is selective about her friends and not all other dogs are tolerant of her energy.  Slow, proper introductions to any new dogs is a MUST with her.  She does not do well with smaller dogs if they are pushy and yappy.

Social with cats: NO CATS … she plays far too rough and has a high prey drive

Good with children:  Her energy may be overwhelming for small children.  Will be better with children 12 years old and up

Adoption donation: $175

We are an all-volunteer group, so please be patient and understand that it takes an average of 7-14 days to process the applications including reference checks, follow-up questions and home visits.  You can expedite the process by providing accurate email addresses for all your references.  Time to make phone calls is limited and we often have multiple applications in process.  We make every effort to move through them as quickly as possible.

When your application is approved, we will schedule a meet-and-greet to see if Mango Grace picks you too.

If it seems that the adoption will be a good match for all, there is an adoption fee, and an adoption contract to be signed.

Please feel free to email weluvpups@hotmail.com if you have additional questions.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Meet Obi! Obi came from the Romulus Animal Shelter, a scared and lonely boy, so quiet and reserved.  He sat quietly, so patient, waiting for his turn out of his kennel every day for potty and a few minutes of love.  He's such a good boy, just needs some basic training that he's never had.  We are not sure about Obi with cats, but he IS dog friendly for sure!! Loves EVERYONE he meets!! Obi is a Pitbull mix, about 2 years old, housebroken, obviously GORGEOUS, and a bundle of laughs and love!

Happy Days Dog and Cat Rescue microchips all dogs and cats before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the shoulder blades and are another form of identification should the animal get lost. The microchips are registered to  Happy Days Dog and Cat Rescue. The adopter's information is added once the adoption is complete. The adopter is responsible for $19.99 fee to change information.  Dogs and Cats still need to have collar with tags should they get lost.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Lilah has the serious expression of her mother, whom we were told is a Great Pyrenees mixed with Anatolian Shepherd. Lilah has the coat and coloring of a Catahoula or Red Heeler, so we're guessing her dad must be some kind of Cow Dog. But it's all just speculation on our part, and the only way to know for sure which breeds contribute to her unique good looks would be to do a DNA test. That's not in our budget, but if you would like to DONATE one, we would be glad to have it done and share the results. :)

Like most Anatolian Shepherds, Lilah is somewhat reserved, loyal to her family and pack, and  distrustful of strangers. This means she doesn't do well at adoption events or even one-on-one in a meet & greet situation, so she gets passed over time and again.  But when you win Lilah over, her loyalty to YOU will be unmatched. 

Lilah could be a great addition to a small homestead, as she has proven to be safe with our goats, sheep, and chickens.  She prefers living inside the house, but goes into the chicken yard with us every day to check things out. 

She has been spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped, so she is ready to start protecting your home as soon as you're ready to start earning her trust.

Apply on our website at www.bluebonnetrescue.org.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
IN A FOSTER HOME IN VISTA, CA.

LUCY was the name her foster chose because when she'd come home and open the door, LUCY would come running...like: LUCY!!! I'm hooooome....

LUCY loves to play with string toys and can even play fetch. She is not much of a cuddler these days. She was at one point but she prefers more independence and can be moody. She only likes things on her terms and is not afraid to make that known! LUCY is best for someone who likes to have a cat around but does not want a lap cat or a cat all over them.

LUCY is pretty small and sleek. Only weighs maybe 6 lbs. LUCY is a fully grown adult and is about 5 years old.

LUCY is housebroken and doesn't spray. As well as current on all shots/vaccinations, has had his rabies shot, is fixed, microchipped and tested negative for FeLV/FIV.

It's unknown whether she gets along with new cats and dogs. She gets along with her foster mom's cats but needs a slow introduction to feel comfortable.

Bring some silly love into your home today!

Please contact Amber directly at: amberfoote@lcad.edu

She is getting more social by the day.  At this point in her socialization she needs a home with a "cat" person, someone who knows and understands how cats' think.

attributes.descriptionHtml:

Miss VIVIEN is a gorgeous girl who is hanging out in her foster home. She was born to a stray mom in a rural area, but a nice lady contacted our rescue to take her in. She always has a fixated concerned look on her face but is quick to lean in for pets and attention. This SWEETHEART gets along great with other cats and probably would do well with a nice dog. Unfortunately Vivien does NOT like children (older teenage adult children may be okay) and would not do well in a home with young children. This girl is the epitome of a couch potato and is looking for a quiet place to land! Email info@ffhsv.org if interested or call a number above!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Gatsby has been with Bobbie's since 2015 and had very little interest. He is a very effectionate boy, listens very well to commands, is eager to please his humans. 

Gatsby is a very happy guy who loves to run, carry around his toys and play fetch with a ball. Oh let me re-phrase that, he is a ball fanatic!

Gatsby enjoys being in the company of his 'humans' and really enjoys extended cuddle sessions on the couch. 

Gatsby is house and crate trained and rides very well in the car.

Gatsby is a little bit too interested in cats, so we recommend a home without them. 

Gatsby is walking nicely on the leash but will get excited when he sees other dogs during walks which should be easily controlled with some professional training. 

Gatsby does guard his food and is used to eat his meals in his crate without a problem. He automatically runs into his crate when it is feeding time, sits and waits until it is his turn. 

Due to his size and energy level we recommend children 6 and up. Please consider giving this gorgeous golden-eyed boy a forever home. He has been waiting for so long and deserves a chance.

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Hi, I’m Sampson! I'm looking for a great home, and I just know there is one out there looking for me too! I am an almost 4-year-old super happy and wiggly and playful guy and weigh in at about 90 lbs. Though I did get pretty lucky in the looks department, I could really care less about all that because all I wanna do is tromp around and play outside and then kick back with my favorite people and wait for dinner to be ready :) I was adopted out into a home with 4 kids originally and would prefer a home without a lot of them now, I'm a low-key guy and that many kids was a lot for me. I would be fine with one or two older ones (around 10+). My anxiety got really high before I was returned and I'm currently on generic Prozac and am doing fabulous! I'm settling into my foster home just great and have a foster sister I love playing with. I would either prefer a no dog or one dog home (the dog MUST be little if there's one already in the home, around 20 lbs). I do love puppies, so if you wanted to adopt me and later on adopt a puppy, I would be fine with that, too! I am housetrained, neutered, vaccinated, and heartworm negative. I'm also not a typical Lab mix, in that my foster mom has seen no destructive tendencies and hasn't seen me chew on any furniture and I would NOT be suitable for a dog park situation. I am a typical Lab mix, though in that I LOVE people, car rides, sleeping on the bed, and eating treats.

If you'd like more info, email your number to rockcityrescue@gmail.com!

attributes.descriptionHtml:
DOB: July 2014

BREED/COLORING: Pointer/ American Staffordshire Terrier Mix; Black & White

SIZE: Robby is about 85lbs and is full grown.

HISTORY: Robby was seen wandering the streets with a huge open wound. His video circulated the online rescue community asking for help – money for vetting, foster home, rescue group. Polysfund stepped in to pay for his care and Foreverhome Pet Rescue has committed to finding him a new home. 

PERSONALITY: Robby is a big, silly boy. He spends a lot of time throwing his bowl around and amusing himself. He's very waggy and kissy - but he's a big boy, so you need to be fairly strong to hold your ground when playing with him and loving on him :) 

TRAINING: Robby has had no previous training so he would require housebreaking and leash training. Robby does not pull on leash and is EXTREMELY playful so we are guessing he'd do very well with obedience training.

WOULD DO BEST: Robby would do best with a strong handler that will play with him and run with him. Another big dog might be good for him too. 

CATS/DOGS/KIDS:  Robby does well with other dogs as long as he has been properly introduced. Robby is not recommended for homes with cats. He is not recommended for homes with children under 10 years old because he is big and goofy and will knock children down.

Vet Record: All of our dogs are currently vaccinated, spayed/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

AVAILABILITY: This dog is available for adoption now and is being fostered or kenneled in the San Fernando Valley area. Please email us and we will send you an adoption application. Local adoptions only (we do not ship dogs).

Visit our website: http://www.foreverhomepetrescue.org/
attributes.name: Robby

attributes.descriptionHtml:
Name: Hazel
Age: DOB 2/27/2016
Gender: Female
Breed: Chihuahua / Rat Terrier
Weight: 15 lbs
Dog friendly: Dog selective
Cat friendly: Yes
Kid friendly: No
House trained: Yes
Crate trained: No
Energy level: Moderate
History: Owner surrender
Adoption Fee: $400

Loving rattie/chi seeks quiet household. 

Some things you will love about Hazel:

  1. Hazel has SASS! She’s rat terrier and chihuahua and somehow she’s extra of each! Anything and everything below that may seem challenging are classic breed characteristics but since Hazel is a little extra, previous rat terrier and/ or chihuahua experience is required to set everyone up for success. 
  2. She loves walks! Other than treats, walks are Hazel’s favorite thing!
  3. Hazel walks very nicely on leash. She either walks next to you or in front of you, but doesn’t pull at the leash.
  4. Hazel loves to snuggle with you. (When she feels like it! I mean, she is a rattie, so she's super independent) Her preferred sleeping spot is under the covers with you! She’s also a perfect date to Netflix & chill with.
  5. Hazel is very food motivated - this makes training so much easier!
  6. Hazel is a great guard dog! She takes her duty to protect the house and her family very seriously. Strangers beware!
  7. Hazel loves toys and will play by herself or with a friend! Hazel loves other dogs, but only the dogs in her family. She currently lives with large and small dogs.  She would love a live-in dog buddy to play with but does not tolerate canine visitors who are seen as a threat that she must protect her family from. Needless to say, occasional play dates and dog parks are out of the question. She is also fine as an only dog.
  8. She doesn’t need a crate! In fact, Hazel has some history with crating and while I’m a staunch supporter of crate training, it will not work for this dog. Fortunately, that’s no problem because she isn’t destructive when left out!

 

Some things to be aware of about Hazel

  1. Hazel is an anxious, fearful little girl. She’s on fluoxetine (doggie Prozac) which is helping a ton, but she’s never going to be a happy-go-lucky kind of gal. She was not well socialized. She is especially afraid of men and kids. Hazel is not a family dog. She would do best with a single person or couple in a quiet household with infrequent visitors. She needs time. and patience. and love. When she knows she’s done well, she gets SO proud of herself and prances and wags her WHOLE body. It will make your entire day.
  2. It takes Hazel a long time to give you her trust. This is a product of her fear and her anxious temperament. Gaining her trust will be an evolution over months, not days or weeks. In the meantime, she needs a safe place to go when needed and someone who will patiently and persistently pursue her love and trust. I’ve found that mostly she wants to feel safe and protected. If you have the patience and are willing to put in the time, winning the trust of a fearful dog will melt. your. heart. Guaranteed.
  3. Hazel is fully housetrained. But. She is a nervous peer and no signal if she needs to go, so you have to pay attention or take her out on a schedule. Her previous owner left pads out as a just-in-case and Hazel was using them. When it rains, Hazel has held it a surprisingly long time. She also poops in the house. It is what it is. 
  4. Hazel is a great guard dog! This is characteristic of her breeds and she takes it very seriously, whether you actually feel threatened or not. She needs a confident handler, experienced with either chihuahuas or rat terriers. Hazel would not fit in a busy household with people/dogs coming and going. Obviously, we all have visitors occasionally and I can help you with how to manage her during these visits.
  5. She hates being left alone and will bark continuously until someone returns. For this reason Hazel cannot live in an apartment or any home with shared walls. Only exception would be retired or working from home post- COVID. Another dog counts as company!

So, admittedly, Hazel is a bit of a challenge at first. But I promise she’s SO worth it. And she deserves a someone who will love and cherish her for every plus and every minus and love her forever.

Ideal would be a person or couple who is home a lot, doesn’t have tons of visitors, may have another dog, and would love to invest in a best friend.

 

Through the course of my veterinary care at Secondhand Hounds it was discovered that I have a systolic click, which can be an early indicator of cardiac disease. After consulting with a cardiologist, it was determined that my heart size and shape is normal, therefore no medication or further treatment is needed at this time. Future adopters should establish a relationship with their primary veterinarian to continue to monitor, and chest x-rays are recommended every 6 months.

attributes.descriptionHtml: Sassy is a beautiful black cat about 6 years old. She was surrendered when her owner had to move away and didn’t want to take her with. She can be a very loving girl but as her name states she can also be VERY sassy and naughty. She has extremely long, beautiful hair. I think once Sassy finds a family that will take care of her she will blossom and become friendlier. Meanwhile a home without any young kids is ideal. She should be fine with all adults, other cats, and calm dogs. The dogs may take a bit for her to warm up to but I think she will do just fine. She will allow you to pet her but you’ve got to know when she’s had enough. She will also play for hours with string toys with her person. She has already been spayed, has tested negative for FELV and FIV, has a micro-chip, and is current on her vaccinations. If you are interested in adopting Sassy please fill out the application at animalrescuefriends.org

attributes.descriptionHtml: Jenny is a sweetheart, so soft and friendly. She always likes to see what we are up to, and when other kitties have gotten bored and wandered off, Jenny is still there to keep us company. Jenny is such a good girl she gets to go outside to roam a bit, and there is nothing she would love more than to be the pet of a gardener! She would not be happy unless she was an indoor and outdoor pet. Company and fresh air, then a nice nap on the sofa would be her nirvana. Jenny comes when called and is gentle, so she would be safe with a child. We think she is about 6 years old and we hope she gets her forever home soon, but we will miss this super girl when she goes. Jenny is fine with other cats and would probable be good with a calm dog too. She is one of our longest residents so if you have room for this sweet girl please consider adoption.

Animal House Shelter tries to keep the environment for the animals in our care, as healthy, stress free and comfortable as possible during their stay with us. Therefore, Walk-Through viewing of the dogs is NOT allowed at the shelter, due to the stress it creates.

During your visit to the shelter, an adoption counselor will assist you through the adoption process and introduce you to as many dogs as you would like to meet, in order to make the best possible match for you, your family and your new pet.

The cats are housed in a large âfree roamâ cat room. They are able to socialize all day with each other, staff, volunteers and potential adopter.

Like people, animals have distinct personalities that make them unique.  At Animal House we are proud to say that these animals are treated like our own. We care enough to be certain they go to the right loving, forever home.
1.	All adoption donations MUST be in cash, money order, travelerâs check , cashierâs check or by VISA, DISCOVER or MASTERCARD credit card only.  NO PERSONAL CHECKS PLEASE.
2.	You must be at least 21 years old to adopt.
3.	All members of the household must be present, including any other dogs you may currently own, in order to do a final adoption (cats do not have to come to the shelter. We will cat test here because we know how stressful it is on the cats to be transported).
4.	Dogs and cats that you currently own must be current on vaccinations and spayed/neutered prior to visiting the shelter or any adoption.
5.	Fill out the Online Application and submit.âVet Reference is necessary if you have owned a pet.
6.	Any adoption may be subject to a âhome checkâ prior to finalization.
7.	We do not allow anyone to put a dog âon holdâ, no exceptions.
8.	Adoption Donations  for dogs & puppies  ranges from $50-$500 (each individual profile will state the adoption donation)
9.	Adoption Donations  for cats & kittens  ranges from $75-$250(each individual profile will state the adoption donation)
10.	Many older dogs and cats have reduced adoption donations which are listed on their individual profiles on the âAdoptable Dogsâ or âAdoptable Catsâ page.
11.	If you are a Senior Citizen-please call or email to ask about our SENIOR to SENIOR Program- When People 65 years or older, with approved application, adopt a pet 8 years or older the adoption donation is waived!
12.	At time of adoption an adoption counselor will take you through the process and answer any questions you may have, as well as ask you questions regarding the adoption.
13.	We have  adoption hours 7 days a week 11am-7pm Mon, Wed, Thurs, Fri, Sun. Tues adoption hours are 11am-4pm. Sat our adoption hours are from 9am-7pm.  There is no appointment necessary.
14.	We are always open during the same hours on holidays.
15.	We  microchip, spay/neuter, heartworm test or FeLV/FIV test  and give vaccinations to all animals.   They are also all on Heartgard Plus & Frontline Plus every month while in our care.  You are also offered pet insurance through ShelterCare.com.
16.	We do require that when you adopt one of our cats/kittens that they are taken home in an appropriate carrier.  You can bring in your own carrier or we can supply you with a cardboard carrier for $10.
Please Remember, all other dogs and family members must be present at the shelter for any final adoption.
attributes.about:
Animal House Shelter is a non-profit, 501(c)3, no kill shelter for all breeds of dogs and cats.

Founded in June 2002, AHS takes in and cares for abused, neglected and abandoned animals â especially those scheduled for euthanasia at other shelters. Once rehabilitated and ready, they are carefully matched with prospective adopters and placed in loving homes. Over 23,000 pets have been adopted from Animal House Shelter.

Like people, animals have distinct personalities that make them unique. At Animal House Shelter, we are proud to say that the dogs and cats are treated like our own. We care enough to be certain they are treated with the comfort and respect that they deserve and we make every effort to ensure that they go to the right, forever, permanent, loving home.

The best possible veterinary care is always given to Animal House Shelter pets and treatment is never declined if it will give the animal a chance for a healthy life. Socializing and keeping our pets happy is also of utmost importance. Dogs are walked 4-5 times daily and cats are housed in a large, whimsical, free-roam habitat All are given loving care and attention by staff and volunteers.

 All dogs and cats are given all vaccinations- including their Rabies vaccine if old enough. They are neutered,  microchipped,  dewormed and heartworm tested (Dogs)  or FeLV/FIV tested (Cats). Dogs are kept on heartworm preventative & all animals receive Frontline Plus monthly by Animal House.

Animal House takes in many special needs animals.  We take care of any ailment or surgery that needs to be done on any animal we rescue including, but not limited to: heart worm treatments, cruciate ligament repair, patella surgery, FHO, heart surgery, diabetes, anxiety disorders, auto immune deficiencies, liver shunts etc.  On average, AHS takes in at least one animal per week that has one of the above ailments or needs surgery.  We do not believe that any animal should be left to be euthanized at a high kill facility because they are sick or injured.  Society has already failed them at one point in time and someone needs to speak up and rescue those that are defenseless and without a voice.  That is who we are are and that is what Animal House Shelter has always been about.  These ailments & surgeries are extremely expensive and we need the communities help to not leave these poor souls to be discarded with no one to care for them.
